This paper deals with the computational complexity of testing and finding plans in probabilistic planning domains, which is a core problem in the field of artificial intelligence. Therefore, cs.AI is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves analyzing the complexity of algorithms, which falls under cs.DS and cs.CC. The use of probabilistic classes such as PP and NP^PP suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of cs.PL, which deals with logic and computation. Finally, the paper's focus on probabilistic planning and algorithmic development suggests that it may also be relevant to the sub-category of cs.LG, which deals with machine learning and probabilistic reasoning.
